Platform Jump

by: Adi Gudi

This game was made for my level 2 project at The League of Amazing Programmers.
Click here to download and play!

1. Why I Made This Game

I decided to make this game because I really enjoy playing platform games such as Doodle Jump and Super Mario Run, and I wanted to create my own version of these games using different power ups and obstacles. Additionally, a lot my friends who already finished this project did games that involved character objects that shot projectiles at the player, so I wanted make my game a bit more unique.

2. What I Learned

From user testing, I learned that the user interface of my game is very creative and fun, especially the background. My teachers and classmates said that my game got too hard as the score increased, so I resolved this problem by adding a power up whenever the score is a multiple of 5, but less or equal to 10. When the player hits the power up, the platforms reset to the speed that the platforms were moving at the beginning of the game, which made it a lot easier for the player to increase their score.

3. Architecture of My Game

My game includes 4 different objects: the Player object, the Lava object, the Platform object, and the Power Up object. The Player object is what the player of the game is controlling, and it works with the Platform object so that when the Player object is on top of a moving platform, the downward velocity is set to zero so that the Player object stays on top of the platform unless the Player object jumps. When the Player object hits the Power Up object, the method that resets the platform speed to the same speed at the beginning of the game is called, and the power up graphic disappears. If the Player object collides with the Lava object's collision box, the drawEndState method is called, which will display the Game Over text, along with the score and high score.

4. Technical Implementation

A particular aspect of my game that I am proud of is the integration of a Power Up. Since my game got too hard as the score increased, I thought that adding a Power Up would make it easier and more capable of getting a higher score. I did this creating a new Power Up object, and programmed it using if statements and collision boxes so that when the Player object intersects the collision box of the Power Up object, the method that resets the platform speed to the same speed at the beginning of the game is called, and the power up graphic disappears.

5. Most Challenging Part

The most challenging part of my game was creating the moving platforms and programming them so that when the Player object is on top of a moving platform, the downward velocity is set to zero so that the Player object stays on top of the platform unless the Player object jumps. A lot of the time the Player object on the moving platform, the Player object goes right through the moving platforms and straight to the lava. This obviously was a big issue, and it was pretty unfair for the player who was playing the game whenever this occurred. I overcame this challenge by changing the downward velocity when the Player object is above the game screen so that the Platform object could detect the Player object's x and y coordinates better, which resolved the problem of the Player object going through the platform.

6. Future Fixes and Updates

Some improvements that I would like to make in the future is to add more power ups so that the game would be more entertaining and fun to play. If I were to continue working on this game, I would want to add more obstacles, such as an enemy shooting projectiles or the finish platform decreasing in width as the score increases.
